<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,698]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
DISCUSSION: 
<taxonomicName box="[357,608,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[357,608,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Pygopleurus rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to group III as definite by 
<bibRefCitation author="Baraud" box="[1030,1205,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refString="Baraud, J. (1989) Revision du genre Pygopleurus Motschulsky (Coleoptera, Scarabaeoidea, Glaphyridae). Annales de la Societe entomologique de France (N. S.), 25 (3), 331 - 375." type="journal article" year="1989">
Baraud (
<number box="[1132,1196,152,178]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" value="1989.0">1989</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. It comes from the area near Mahabad in northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[586,636,192,218]" name="Iran" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Iran</collectingCountry>
, where 
<taxonomicName authority="Mitter" authorityName="Mitter" box="[733,1077,192,218]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[733,995,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Pygopleurus anahitae</emphasis>
Mitter
</taxonomicName>
was also described, and with which it can be easily confused (see description in 
<bibRefCitation author="Mitter" box="[747,887,232,258]" pageId="3" pageNumber="64" refString="Mitter, H. (2001) Notizen uber wenig bekannte Arten der Familie Glaphyridae aus dem Nahen und Mittleren Osten und Beschreibung von Pygopleurus anahitae n. sp. (Coleoptera, Scarabaeoidea, Glaphyridae). Linzer biologische Beitrage, 33 (2), 1041 - 1045." type="journal article" year="2001">
Mitter 
<number box="[827,887,232,258]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) due to similarity in external morphology. We were able to compare the series of 
<taxonomicName box="[555,678,272,297]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[555,678,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with various specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[997,1127,272,297]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[997,1127,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: one 
<typeStatus box="[1192,1293,272,298]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">paratype</typeStatus>
(male), five topotypes (two males, three females) from the 
<typeStatus box="[714,765,312,338]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">type</typeStatus>
locality and same collecting event as the 
<typeStatus box="[1271,1377,312,338]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">holotype</typeStatus>
, five specimens from locations very near to the 
<typeStatus box="[650,700,352,378]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">type</typeStatus>
locality, and three specimens from new localities. A differential diagnosis follows, and illustrations of the two species are presented.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,698]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
<taxonomicName box="[198,321,432,457]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[198,321,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily separated from 
<taxonomicName box="[612,744,432,457]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[612,744,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of parameres: compared with those of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are much more elongated and narrower in the distal part, almost straight and not curved in dorsal view, the apex is more obliquely truncated (
<figureCitation box="[682,816,512,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 13. 9 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1934,1955]" captionTargetBox="[216,1348,826,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,791,1908]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 13. 9 – 11: Pygopleurus rapuzzii n. sp.: 9, male, right paramere, lateral view (holotype); 10, male, right paramere, dorsal view (holotype); 11, female, right genital valves (allotype). 12 – 13: Pygopleurus anahitae Mitter: 12, male, right paramere, lateral view (topotype); 13, female, right genital valves (topotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183096/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Figs. 9, 12</figureCitation>
). Moreover, 
<taxonomicName box="[980,1106,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[980,1106,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[1269,1403,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[1269,1403,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in external morphology by the absence of the longitudinal clypeal carina, the clypeus being simply thickened medially (the carina is usually strong in 
<taxonomicName box="[643,777,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[643,777,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can nevertheless be obsolete in some small specimens), and by the posterior angles of the pronotum being not marked, whereas they are marked although rounded in 
<taxonomicName box="[284,416,672,698]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[284,299,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[314,416,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183096/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" targetBox="[216,1348,826,1875]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1934,2014]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,311,1934,1955]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">FIGURES 9–13</emphasis>
. 9–11: 
<taxonomicName box="[389,593,1934,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[389,593,1934,1955]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Pygopleurus rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[600,654,1934,1955]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
: 9, male, right paramere, lateral view (holotype); 10, male, right paramere, dorsal view (holotype); 11, female, right genital valves (allotype). 12–13: 
<taxonomicName authority="Mitter" authorityName="Mitter" box="[824,1109,1964,1985]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[824,1037,1964,1985]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Pygopleurus anahitae</emphasis>
Mitter
</taxonomicName>
: 12, male, right paramere, lateral view (topotype); 13, female, right genital valves (topotype).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">
The females of the two species can be easily recognized by the presence/absence of the clypeal carina (
<figureCitation box="[159,278,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1979,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1394,156,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[163,1411,141,1976]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 5: Pygopleurus rapuzzii n. sp.: 1, male (holotype); 2, male (paratype); 3, female (allotype); 4, female (paratype); 5, head of female (allotype). 6 – 8: Pygopleurus anahitae Mitter: 6, male (topotype); 7, female (topotype); 8, head of female (topotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183095/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">Figs. 5, 8</figureCitation>
), and, in addition, by the different structure of the apex of the elytra, which is distinctly more pointed in the new species than in 
<taxonomicName box="[560,692,232,257]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[560,692,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the same way, the genital valves of the females are clearly different (
<figureCitation box="[267,408,272,298]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 13. 9 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1934,1955]" captionTargetBox="[216,1348,826,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,791,1908]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 13. 9 – 11: Pygopleurus rapuzzii n. sp.: 9, male, right paramere, lateral view (holotype); 10, male, right paramere, dorsal view (holotype); 11, female, right genital valves (allotype). 12 – 13: Pygopleurus anahitae Mitter: 12, male, right paramere, lateral view (topotype); 13, female, right genital valves (topotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183096/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">Figs. 11, 13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">
The integument colour of these two species may also provide additional diagnostic characters, but the limited samples we could study do not allow a proper evaluation. To date, 
<taxonomicName box="[990,1122,352,377]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[990,1122,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from specimens having dark purple to violet-black head and pronotum in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[1027,1140,392,418]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1979,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1394,156,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[163,1411,141,1976]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 5: Pygopleurus rapuzzii n. sp.: 1, male (holotype); 2, male (paratype); 3, female (allotype); 4, female (paratype); 5, head of female (allotype). 6 – 8: Pygopleurus anahitae Mitter: 6, male (topotype); 7, female (topotype); 8, head of female (topotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183095/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">
Figs. 
<number box="[1093,1140,392,418]" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7</number>
</figureCitation>
), while the same is green to bright purple in 
<taxonomicName box="[370,493,432,457]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[370,493,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">P. rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males (
<figureCitation box="[585,698,432,458]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1979,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1394,156,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[163,1411,141,1976]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 5: Pygopleurus rapuzzii n. sp.: 1, male (holotype); 2, male (paratype); 3, female (allotype); 4, female (paratype); 5, head of female (allotype). 6 – 8: Pygopleurus anahitae Mitter: 6, male (topotype); 7, female (topotype); 8, head of female (topotype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183095/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">
Figs. 
<number box="[651,698,432,458]" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Females may show less difference in the colour of pronotum (although darker in 
<taxonomicName box="[386,510,472,497]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[386,510,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">P. rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) but seem to be different for the elytral pattern, bicoloured in 
<taxonomicName box="[1252,1386,472,497]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anahitae">
<emphasis box="[1252,1386,472,497]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">P. anahitae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and monochromatic in 
<taxonomicName box="[372,495,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[372,495,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">P. rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">
Despite intraspecific colour variations being common to many 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1081,552,577]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[933,1081,552,577]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">Pygopleurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, 
<taxonomicName box="[1187,1437,552,577]" class="Insecta" family="Glaphyridae" genus="Pygopleurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapuzzii">
<emphasis box="[1187,1437,552,577]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">Pygopleurus rapuzzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is noteworthy for the sexual dichroism of the head and pronotum and for the black form of the female, which are both unusual among this genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,738]" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">
DERIVATIO NOMINIS: In homage to Pierpaolo Rapuzzi from Prepotto (
<collectingCountry box="[1015,1074,672,698]" name="Italy" pageId="4" pageNumber="63">Italy</collectingCountry>
), the collector of the first specimen of this new species that we studied.
</paragraph>
